{
  "texts": [
    "However, the general case is quite involved and therefore we postpone the relevant definitions to Subsection 2.1.",
    "We continue here by considering only the top-dimensional case of d-currents in R d, which is the most important for this paper.",
    "Fortunately, this case also requires no knowledge of the Federer-Fleming theory of currents and we may restrict our attention to only classical distributions.Every metric d-current T in R d defines a distribution Cd T via the formula Cd T (φ) = T (φ, x 1,..., x d) for φ ∈ C ∞ c (R d).",
    "Here, for each j = 1,..., d, the symbol x j stands for the coordinate function x → x j and C ∞ c (R d) is the space of smooth compactly supported functions.",
    "It is instructive to verify that if M ⊂ R d is a d-dimensional manifold with the canonical orientation, then Cd M is the distribution given by the L 1 loc -function χ M (characteristic function of M)."
  ]
}